attributes.description: A financially motivated threat actor gained initial access to a web server by executing a Base64-encoded command through a "Node.js" process, likely by exploiting CVE-2025-55182. This command initiated the download and execution of a malicious shell script from an actor-controlled server. Following this, the actor deployed multiple persistence mechanisms to maintain access, including modifying shell startup files, creating cron jobs, and establishing new systemd services. The actor also dropped a JavaScript-based malware component identified as "HOTTEA." The primary objective was achieved when the actor executed a script with elevated privileges to hijack the servers "Nginx" configuration. This script systematically replaced existing configurations to redirect all legitimate website traffic to a malicious domain likely for phishing or further malware distribution, before reloading the web server service to activate the changes.

attributes.description:
Google Threat Intelligence Group (GTIG) is tracking the active exploitation of vulnerability `CVE-2025-55182` in Node.js runtime environments. This vulnerability allows for Remote Code Execution (RCE) and is being leveraged by threat actors to download and execute arbitrary payloads on compromised Linux hosts.

GTIG has observed adversaries exploiting this flaw to spawn command shells directly from the parent Node.js process. Attackers are utilizing "Living off the Land" (LOTL) techniques, abusing native system binaries such as `wget`, `curl`, and `python` to evade detection while retrieving malicious tools from remote infrastructure masquerading as legitimate services.

Following a successful exploitation, GTIG has observed the deployment of secondary capabilities, including: 
1. Executing obfuscated downloader chains to retrieve intermediate stager scripts; 
2. Conducting system reconnaissance and creating staging directories to ensure payload compatibility; 
3. Deploying and executing malicious payloads, specifically the SNOWLIGHT malware and illicit cryptominers, using utilities like nohup to maintain execution.

`CVE-2025-55182` was added to CISA's Known Exploited Vulnerabilities Catalog on December 5, 2025, with a mandatory remediation deadline of December 26, 2025.

value.title: Registry Tampering by Potentially Suspicious Processes
value.author: Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects suspicious registry modifications made by suspicious processes such as script engine processes such as WScript, or CScript etc.
These processes are rarely used for legitimate registry modifications, and their activity may indicate an attempt to modify the registry
without using standard tools like regedit.exe or reg.exe, potentially for evasion and persistence.
